text:
(1)

4048 Hubbard Place, south side, just west of Kings Highway, formerly known as Hubbard's Homestead, at 13 Hubbard Place. This house was built in 1705, and was occupied by the Rev. Ulpianus Van Sinderen, who died in 1796. In 1860 it was occupied by Misses E. and J. Ditmas and since 1906 by Harry Fisher, an actor.

1922.

Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.

(2)

The same, as seen west from Kings Highway. The first house at the left, is the Hubbard Homestead.

1922.

Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.

(3)

The same, showing the north side of Hubbard Place, opposite the Hubbard's Homestead.

1922.

Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.
title: Brooklyn: Hubbard Place - Kings Highway

text:
4048 Hubbard Place, south side, west of King's Highway, once known as No. 13 Hubbard Place, showing The Hubbard Homestead, believed to have been built in 1705 by the Ditmas Family. This house was known as the "Little House with the Windmill", also as the Van Sinderen House having been the home of the Rev. Tiplianus Van Sinderen for whom it was built. The Reverend served as pastor for the Dutch Reformed Church from 1742 to 1796, when he died. This house was occupied by the Misses E. and J. Ditmas in 1860 and by Harry Fisher, the owner since 1906; it is still standing (1936). 1922.

Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.

The same, from a different angle.
1922.

Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.

The same, from a different angle.
1922.

Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.

The same, from another angle.
October 1928.

Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.
